<!--
  EtherCAT I/O hardware tree for the Shark project (see Sync/IoManifestParser.cs).
  Originally transcribed from images/devices.jpg (Solution Explorer capture of
  the live PLC_NFL_SHARK project's I/O tree) — but that screenshot's visual
  nesting (Box(CU2508) -> Box(EK1100) -> Terminals) does NOT match how the
  real Shark.tsproj actually stores the tree, confirmed by reading the real
  file's raw XML nesting depth directly (2026-07-14):

  BH1: "Box 1 (CU2508)" and "EK1100_1.1" are SIBLINGS (both direct children of
  BH1) — EK1100_1.1 is the one that actually carries the 8 terminal children.
  BH2: "Box 44 (CU2508)" and "EK1100_2.1" are ALSO siblings of each other, and
  EK1100_2.1 itself has NO children at all — every one of BH2's 19 remaining
  terminals is nested under the FIRST terminal, "EL3174_2.1", not under
  EK1100_2.1 (apparently TwinCAT's own on-disk chain/bus-order representation
  for this coupler, not a real ownership relationship).

  This matters because Sync/IoSyncEngine.cs's DeleteOrphans prunes any real
  direct child not declared here. The previous (wrong) nesting caused
  EK1100_1.1/EK1100_2.1/EL3174_2.1 to look like undeclared orphans and
  triggered DeleteChild on them — which would have deleted almost all of
  BH1/BH2's real hardware (an in-flight COM RPC failure happened to prevent
  the delete from completing; see tasks/todo.md). Keep this manifest's
  nesting in exact sync with the real project's structure, not the
  screenshot's visual grouping — verify against the real .tsproj's raw XML
  indentation before changing this file again.

  BH3 added 2026-07-16, this time by reading the real reference project's
  on-disk config directly (PLC_NFL_SHARK\_Config\IO\BH3\), not a screenshot
  — its main .tsproj only references three EtherCAT devices (BH1/BH2/BH3; a
  fourth, "Device 1 (RT-Ethernet Adapter)", isn't an EL/EK terminal device).
  BH4/BH5 from the earlier screenshot don't exist anywhere in this reference
  project snapshot — they must belong to a different revision/machine, so
  they're deliberately NOT added here; don't guess them back in.

  BH3's own nesting (unlike BH1/BH2) is flat and unambiguous, confirmed from
  "Term 33 (EK1100).xti" directly: "Box 32 (CU2508)" and "Term 33 (EK1100)"
  are siblings (same pattern as BH1/BH2's own CU2508/EK1100 siblings), and
  Term 33's five terminals are all its own direct children — no chain-quirk
  nesting to worry about here. BH3 is a TwinSAFE safety hookup (EL1918 =
  TwinSAFE Logic terminal, EL2904 = TwinSAFE safe digital outputs) — its own
  .xti has an internal <Mappings> section, but those are terminal-to-terminal
  FSOE safety-bus routing (EL1918 <-> EL2904), NOT PLC-variable links.
  GVL_Safety.st's own AT %I*/%Q* variables (SafetyOk/SafetyRunning/etc.)
  route through the Safety-project's own instance mapping in the main
  .tsproj (a <Safety><Instance><Mappings><MappingInfo GUID-based> block) — a
  separate, more specialized mechanism than io-devices.xml's <Links>/
  links.xml, out of scope for this manifest.

  No real digital-IO-to-variable wiring (which channel each %I/%Q variable in
  PRG_DIGITAL_INPUT.st/PRG_DIGITAL_OUTPUT.st/etc. is actually wired to) exists
  anywhere on disk in the reference project for BH1/BH2/BH3 — confirmed by
  directly reading every .xti file, not just BH3's. Populating real <Links>/
  links.xml entries for those is still blocked on the actual physical wiring,
  which only a human with the panel/schematic can supply.

  All devices stay Disabled="true": an enabled EtherCAT master with no
  variable linked to a task blocks the build with a modal "needs sync master"
  dialog (see IoManifestParser's doc comment) — confirmed live (2026-07-15,
  see tasks/plan.md) when a links.xml applied via ConsumeMappingInfo silently
  didn't actually resolve anything and the build hung until force-killed.
  Only flip a device to Disabled="false" once its <Links>/links.xml entries
  are confirmed real and applied successfully.
-->
